<tr>
<td>
<center>
<div class="noprint plainlinksneverexpand navbar" style="background:none; padding:0; font-weight:normal;; font-size:xx-small;">This box: <a href="/wiki/Template:English_grammar" title="Template:English grammar"><span title="View this template" style="">view</span></a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="/wiki/Template_talk:English_grammar" title="Template talk:English grammar"><span title="Discussion about this template" style="">talk</span></a>&#160;•&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:English_grammar&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:English_grammar&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow"><span title="Edit this template" style=";">edit</span></a></div>
</center>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>English grammar</b> is a body of rules (<a href="/wiki/Grammar" title="Grammar">grammar</a>) specifying how phrases and sentences are constructed in the <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English language</a>. Accounts of English grammar tend to fall into two groups: the <i>descriptivist</i>, which describes the grammatical system of English; and the <i>prescriptivist</i>, which does not describe English grammar but rather sets out a small list of social regulations that attempt to govern the linguistic behaviour of native speakers (see <a href="/wiki/Linguistic_prescription" title="Linguistic prescription">Linguistic prescription</a> and <a href="/wiki/Descriptive_linguistics" title="Descriptive linguistics">Descriptive linguistics</a>). Prescriptive grammar concerns itself with several open <a href="/wiki/Disputes_in_English_grammar" title="Disputes in English grammar">disputes in English grammar</a>, often representing changes in usage over time.</p>
<p>This article <i>describes</i> a generalized <a href="/wiki/Standard_English" title="Standard English">Standard English</a>, which is the form of speech found in types of public discourse including broadcasting, education, entertainment, government, and news reporting. Standard English includes both formal and informal speech. The many <a href="/wiki/List_of_dialects_of_the_English_language" title="List of dialects of the English language">dialects of English</a> have divergences from the grammar described here, which are only cursorily mentioned.</p>
